	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.30]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have to agree with a previous response.&nbsp;&nbsp;The party you were in were either newbies or idiots.  If you call incoming, the group needs to be ready and aware.  If they choose to sit and med while one person tanks, they are dangerous players.  <br><br>At lower levels (fighting in Oasis for XP qualifies) it doesn't really matter who pulls as long as they have a clue about what they are doing.  The person who pulls should be aware of agro radius on the mobs and able to throw or shoot at mobs effectively (or learning to do so).<br><br>On many of my pulling adventures through the levels, I used various methods to attract a mob ranging from standing near the mob, hitting it once with a special attack, and throwing axes, shurikens, or daggers at it.  <br><br>On a side note, I have always found that players that try to tell someone how to play their class (while grouped with them), are full of crap and should be ignored, unless the person receiving the information is doing a horrible job in their class.  One of my favorite lines when I play a character other than my monk is "if you have any questions ask me, I may know something that will prevent your death".  Beyond that...its up to them to ask the questions, I do not give instruction without the monk asking.  <br><br>I do not claim to be an expert, but have been a monk for a long time...geez...it has been a long time...doh...<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
